# The Executive Board

**The Executive Board**

The Executive Board is made up of the five elected officers – the President, AVP, MVP, Secretary and Treasurer. Those are the ONLY members of the Executive Board. International MOMS Club does not recognize co-officers.

- The Executive Board must preview and approve any and all activities and expenditures to come before the membership. For more about this, see the Chapter Manual.
- While the Board must approve all activities and expenditures before presenting them to the membership at a monthly business meeting, the final approval for all activities and expenditures comes from the membership. The members must vote on all activities and expenditures, and all voting must happen at the regular monthly business meetings. For more information about this, see the Chapter Manual.
- Only the five elected officers may attend Board meetings unless they specifically invite additional members or appointed officers to make a presentation. If others are invited, those non-Board members should make their presentations at the beginning of the meeting and then leave, so the Board can discuss the presentation or other business in private.
- Board meetings may be held at night only with unanimous consent of the five Board members. If even one Board member requests to hold Board meetings during the day, the Board meetings must be held during the day.
- The Board meeting should be noted on the chapter calendar, so members know when to submit ideas to the officers. The time and location do not have to be posted, as Board meetings are not open to the full membership.

If you have any questions about Board Meetings or voting, see your Chapter Manual and talk to your Coordinator.

---

**Ideas for Board Meeting Agendas**

Having an agenda makes any meeting run more smoothly. While you can go through old business, then new business, we've found it's easier to have each officer go through whatever they're handling at the time, and then handle anything that doesn't easily fall under a particular officer at the end. Most topics will fall under at least one of the officers' duties.

- Start with the President's report – talk about anything you are handling and get input from the other officers.
- Take the other officers in turn – AVP, MVP, Secretary, Treasurer.
- Make sure to VOTE on any decisions that need to be made. Understand that the Board's vote is usually not the final decision – the membership must also vote on everything the chapter does and all money the chapter spends. For more information on this, see the Chapter Manual and talk to your Coordinator.
- Some other things to review at a Board meeting (can come under specific officers' reports or separately):
    - How did the last meeting go? Any ideas for improvement? Anything work particularly well? Ideas for future meeting speakers or activities? (Could be under President's time, AVP's or MVP's…)
    - How many new members, renewing members, non-renewing members are there? Identify any members you have not seen for a while and think of ways to contact them and encourage them to come. (Could be under MVP, Secretary or Treasurer's topics…)
    - Always review the treasury – how much income did the chapter have and how much in expenses? Compare this to the budget to make sure it is on track. If not, make plans to go to the membership to adjust it. (Under Treasurer's report…)
    - Review how the playgroups are doing. (Under MVP or AVP…)
    - Discuss how the current service project planning is going and what the Service Committee may need to move to the next step. (Under AVP report…)
    - Review the calendar to be proposed to the membership at the next business meeting and decide who will present the items for vote. (Normally part of the end-of-Board-meeting summary…)
- Be sure that everyone's ideas are treated respectfully and that all ideas are voted on.
- All topics and votes should be included in the Board minutes by the Secretary.

For more information about committees, voting, minutes, and meetings, see your Chapter manual and talk to your Coordinator.

